From cou.: 1 Digital simulations are a commonly used tool in electrochemical and electroanalytical research. However, even though the employed computational methods often feature significant complexity, testing routines are rarely specified or discussed in literature. In this work, we address this topic and describe approaches towards testing electrochemical simulation software. While focussing on simple systems featuring Nernstian reactions in 1:1 stoichiometries, we guide through rigorous testing processes of one- and two dimensional simulations with regard to applications in cyclic voltammetry. To this end, we compile expressions for the calculation of key values as references, discuss the conduction of convergence studies, and suggest approaches to automated software testing.
From Soup: 1 Digital simulations are a commonly used tool in electrochemical and electroanalytical research. However, even though the employed computational methods often feature significant complexity, testing routines are rarely specified or discussed in literature. In this work, we address this topic and describe approaches towards testing electrochemical simulation software. While focussing on simple systems featuring Nernstian reactions in 1 : 1 stoichiometries, we guide through rigorous testing processes of one- and two dimensional simulations with regard to applications in cyclic voltammetry. To this end, we compile expressions for the calculation of key values as references, discuss the conduction of convergence studies, and suggest approaches to automated software testing.
 ###### 
From cou.: 2 Recent decades have seen fast advances in a number of different fields of electroanalytical and electrochemical research including microelectrodes,1,2 nanoelectrodes,3,4 fast-scan cyclic voltammetry methods,5 and generator-collector or redox-cycling systems.6,7 In addition to progresses in experimental methods, these developments have often been facilitated by a detailed theoretical understanding of the respective systems, which was obtained from a mathematical or computational modelling. Digital electrochemical simulations are hence a widely used tool in today's electroanalytical research. With the increasing availability of and continuous advances in computational power, we have observed a growing number of publications on electrochemical simulations using either in-house-developed or widely-available commercial8 software. Such digital simulations can now be commonly found in literature while applications include diffusion-controlled electrode processes,9,10 nano-impact experiments,11–13 the modelling of single-molecule detection,14 electrochemical noise characteristics,15,16 and nano-scale effects like hydrodynamic adsorption.17 A number of different approaches have further been discussed in great detail in the textbooks18,19 by Compton and Britz.
From Soup: 2 Recent decades have seen fast advances in a number of different fields of electroanalytical and electrochemical research including microelectrodes, 1,2 nanoelectrodes, 3,4 fast-scan cyclic voltammetry methods, 5 and generator-collector or redox-cycling systems. 6,7 In addition to progresses in experimental methods, these developments have often been facilitated by a detailed theoretical understanding of the respective systems, which was obtained from a mathematical or computational modelling. Digital electrochemical simulations are hence a widely used tool in today's electroanalytical research. With the increasing availability of and continuous advances in computational power, we have observed a growing number of publications on electrochemical simulations using either in-house-developed or widely-available commercial 8 software. Such digital simulations can now be commonly found in literature while applications include diffusion-controlled electrode processes, 9,10 nano-impact experiments, 11–13 the modelling of single-molecule detection, 14 electrochemical noise characteristics, 15,16 and nano-scale effects like hydrodynamic adsorption. 17 A number of different approaches have further been discussed in great detail in the textbooks 18,19 by Compton and Britz.
 ###### 
From cou.: 3 Alongside the growing number of publications in this field, an increasing complexity of employed methods can be observed. This complexity may, for instance, arise from the application of sophisticated solvers, the coupling of large numbers of reactions or diffusion processes, the modelling of complex geometries, or the use of parallel computing on CPUs or GPUs. Additionally, simulations may include several thousand lines of code, which may reduce the facility of easy inspection. Hence, the definition and performance of rigorous testing processes is crucial in the development of such simulations.
From Soup: 3 Alongside the growing number of publications in this field, an increasing complexity of employed methods can be observed. This complexity may, for instance, arise from the application of sophisticated solvers, the coupling of large numbers of reactions or diffusion processes, the modelling of complex geometries, or the use of parallel computing on CPUs or GPUs. Additionally, simulations may include several thousand lines of code, which may reduce the facility of easy inspection. Hence, the definition and performance of rigorous testing processes is crucial in the development of such simulations.
 ###### 
From cou.: 4 In the following, we present a number of different tests for electrochemical simulations that are either generally applicable or that can specifically be used to assess one- or two-dimensional simulations. We provide expressions for theoretical reference values, discuss the conduction of convergence studies, and suggest a method for automated software testing. The pass of each test is a necessary requirement for successful modelling, even though it alone can never provide a sufficient validation. The results discussed deliver rather a number of strong indicators that can be used to evaluate if a software works correctly. Aside from the theoretical discussion, we additionally present the application of some testing procedures to an example simulation, which employs a finite difference approach to model cyclic voltammetry at a macro electrode. The methods presented, however, are equally applicable to simulations based on any other modelling approach, such as finite elements8 or random walks.9,10
From Soup: 4 In the following, we present a number of different tests for electrochemical simulations that are either generally applicable or that can specifically be used to assess one- or two-dimensional simulations. We provide expressions for theoretical reference values, discuss the conduction of convergence studies, and suggest a method for automated software testing. The pass of each test is a necessary requirement for successful modelling, even though it alone can never provide a sufficient validation. The results discussed deliver rather a number of strong indicators that can be used to evaluate if a software works correctly. Aside from the theoretical discussion, we additionally present the application of some testing procedures to an example simulation, which employs a finite difference approach to model cyclic voltammetry at a macro electrode. The methods presented, however, are equally applicable to simulations based on any other modelling approach, such as finite elements 8 or random walks. 9,10
