From Soup: 55 Table 3 presents an overview of applicable tests for a number of different simulation types. The total number of molecules ( K n = const.) can be used as a test in all electrochemical simulations, while the point-wise summation of concentrations ( K c = const.) can be additionally applied if both species feature equal diffusion coefficients. In the case of reversible reactions, the peak separation Δ E pp can be used as a measure and the peak height I p can be compared to theoretical values for both micro- and macroelectrodes. Furthermore, mid-point potentials E mid and half-wave potentials E 1/2 can be controlled in the one- and two-dimensional cases, respectively. Chronoamperograms at large overpotentials can further be compared to the Cottrell equation for macro-electrodes and to the Shoup–Szabo equation for micro-disk electrodes.
