From Soup: 56 The above-discussed methods provide a number of tests and theory values that can be applied to or compared with simulation results. However, since simulation approaches such as finite differences or random walks are numerical methods, the simulation results obtained will never exactly match theory values but converge to them. Convergence then depends on a number of different parameters that may either be intrinsic parameters of the simulation method or the employed computational means. For instance, results may converge with a decreasing grid spacing in a finite difference simulation or with the a decrease in the spatial displacement in a random walk, while they may additionally converge with increasing bit depth of the floating-point variables used in the computation. It is hence crucial to identify all simulation parameters (or sets of interdependent parameters) that impact the accuracy of the simulation results and to perform rigorous convergence studies on them.
