From cou.: 59 Table 3 presents an overview of applicable tests for a number of different simulation types. The total number of molecules (Kn = const.) can be used as a test in all electrochemical simulations, while the point-wise summation of concentrations (Kc = const.) can be additionally applied if both species feature equal diffusion coefficients. In the case of reversible reactions, the peak separation ΔEpp can be used as a measure and the peak height Ip can be compared to theoretical values for both micro- and macroelectrodes. Furthermore, mid-point potentials Emid and half-wave potentials E1/2 can be controlled in the one- and two-dimensional cases, respectively. Chronoamperograms at large overpotentials can further be compared to the Cottrell equation for macro-electrodes and to the Shoup–Szabo equation for micro-disk electrodes.
From Soup: 59 Fig. 2 presents the results of all quantities Q i for Δ X ( X = 0) being varied in a range of seven orders of magnitude from 10 −3 to 10 −10 . Given the required accuracy of the simulation, the respective minimum value for Δ X ( X = 0) can be found in the plot as the highest value of Δ X ( X = 0) that satisfies all accuracy targets.
